{"questionId":"11912","questionHtml":"<p>Hence, show that a data set with only 5 numbers in it cannot have any outliers.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"UQ + 1.5IQR = 1.25{x_4} + 1.25{x_5} - 0.75{x_1} - 0.75{x_2} \\geqslant {x_5}\">\n  <mi>U</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.5</mn>\n  <mi>I</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mi>R</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩾</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>M1A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>Since&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"1.25{x_4} + 0.25{x_5} \\geqslant 0.75{x_1} + 0.75{x_2}\">\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>0.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩾</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;due to the ascending order.&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em>R1</em></strong></p>\n<p>Similarly&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"LQ - 1.5IQR = 1.25{x_1} + 1.25{x_2} - 0.75{x_4} - 0.75{x_5} \\leqslant {x_1}\">\n  <mi>L</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>1.5</mn>\n  <mi>I</mi>\n  <mi>Q</mi>\n  <mi>R</mi>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>−</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>5</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>M1A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>Since&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"0.25{x_1} + 1.25{x_2} \\leqslant 0.75{x_3} + 0.75{x_4}\">\n  <mn>0.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>1.25</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>⩽</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>0.75</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;due to the ascending order.</p>\n<p>So there are no outliers for a data set of 5 numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>AG</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong><em>[5 marks]</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>","meta":{"questionId":"11912","referenceCode":"EXM.1.SL.TZ0.2b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, show that a data set with only 5 numbers in it cannot have any outliers.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.1—Concepts, reliability and sampling techniques"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}